nkrijk","Salwick, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Salwick, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1334–":"about 1334–Deceased","1334–Female":"1334–Deceased","1365–1405":"1365–1405","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1353–1382":"1353–1382","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1321–1386":"1321–1386","1340–1395":"1340–1395","before 1365":"before 1365","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1334":"1334","1355":"1355","1453":"1453","1321":"1321","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1386":"1386","about 1334":"about 1334","about 1352":"about 1352","1405":"1405","Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England":"Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England","England":"England","London, England":"London, England","Salwick, Lancashire, England":"Salwick, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Salwick, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Salwick, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"West","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and German: from Middle English, Middle High German <i>west</i> ‘west’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived to the west of a settlement, or a habitational name for someone who had migrated from further west.","Americanized form of Finnish <b>Vesterinen</b>: from the personal name <i>Vesteri</i> (a short form of   Sylvester  ) + the surname suffix <i>-nen</i>.","History: This name was brought to North America independently by many bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. Thomas West, 12th Baron De La Warre, was captain general of Virginia in 1610–11. The state of DE is named for him. One of the earliest permanent settlers was Francis West (1606–92), who came to Duxbury, MA, from Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, in or before 1638."],"variants":[{"name":"Western","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>westerne</i> ‘western’, denoting ‘(the man from the) west’. Compare   West   and   Wester  .","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Vestern, found in two places, a compound of <i>vest</i> ‘west’ + <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’, denoting a farm to the west."]},{"name":"Sylvester","meanings":["English and German: from the Middle English and Latin personal name <i>Silvester</i> ‘dweller in the forest’ (a derivative of <i>silva</i> ‘wood’). The name was borne by three popes, including a contemporary of Constantine the Great, and seems to have been first used in England by clerics."]},{"name":"Westman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Birgit, Erik, Hilmer, Nels.","Swedish: ornamental or topographic name from (an altered form of) the elements <i>väst</i> ‘west’ + <i>-man</i>. It is also found in Finland.","Americanized form of German <b>Westmann</b>: variant of   West  , with the addition of Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":3,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":48,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Eleanor West was born about 1334, in Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England, her father, Sir Thomas West, was 14 and her mother, Alice FitzHerbert, was -4. She married Sir Nicholas de Clifton about 1352, in Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in England, and was buried in London, England."},"et":{"about 1334–":"umbes 1334–Surnud","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","1365–1405":"1365–1405","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1353–1382":"1353–1382","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1321–1386":"1321–1386","1340–1395":"1340–1395","before 1365":"enne 1365","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1334":"1334","1355":"1355","1453":"1453","1321":"1321","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1386":"1386","about 1334":"umbes 1334","about 1352":"umbes 1352","1405":"1405","Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England":"Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England","England":"England","London, England":"